   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="uoedh_hl_h.3175_1.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <address rend="letterhead">
                  <addrLine>The Little Orchard,</addrLine>
                  <addrLine>Shoreham,</addrLine>
                  <addrLine>Kent</addrLine>
               </address>

               <dateline>
                  <milestone unit="section" xml:id="m01"/>
                  <date when="1914-01-17"> Jan 17. 14</date>
               </dateline>
               <salute>My dear friend:</salute>
               <milestone unit="section" xml:id="m02"/>
            </opener>

            <p>Best thanks for <choice><abbr>yr.</abbr><expan>your</expan></choice> last nice long
               letter, full of news. Also very many thanks for the fine poem in the "<name
                  type="newspaper" ref="TheSphere">Sphere</name>". There are beautiful lines in it.
               But of course it is <hi rend="underline">very</hi> sad.</p>

            <p>I have not seen the magazine <add place="above"><unclear>conducted</unclear></add> by
               the "uppish" young poets. Possibly there may be good things in it now &amp; again,
               for as <persName ref="#ps:EdmundGosse">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>
                  Gosse</persName> thinks there is a great deal of <pb n="2"
                  facs="uoedh_hl_h.3175_2.jpg"/>
               <milestone xml:id="m03" unit="section"/> almost good verse published. I think
                  <persName ref="#ps:MillicentWedmore">Miss Wedmore</persName>'s <add place="above"
                  >must be</add> very much above the ordinary, don't you? and I see there is a young
                  <persName ref="#ps:ArthurBell">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Arthur
                  Bell</persName> very much praised.</p>

            <p>I was really impressed by <persName ref="#ps:FrankTaylor">Frank Taylor</persName>'s
                  "<name type="poetry-anthology">The Gallant Way</name>". They are of course <hi
                  rend="underline">soldier</hi> poems, &amp; they have a splendid ring &amp; "go"
               about them. One on "<name type="poem">Minden</name>" – and another on "<name
                  type="poem">Blucher</name>" – &amp; a 3<hi rend="superscript">rd</hi>. about
                  "<name type="poem">The Men <pb n="3" facs="uoedh_hl_h.3175_3.jpg"/>
                  <milestone xml:id="m04" unit="section"/> Who Lead</name>" are <hi rend="underline"
                  >excellent</hi> beyond dispute.</p>

            <p>What do you think of this craze for "films"? I see you say "<ref
                  target="#bib:Hardy1874_FarFromTheMaddingCrowd">Far from the Madding Crowd</ref>"
               is to be done. I wonder if the system makes people lazy about reading, &amp; less
               keen about genuine drama?</p>

            <p>I am so glad you have written about performing animals. There <hi rend="underline"
                  >may</hi> be a few cases in which <del>a few </del>
               <add place="above">they</add> are kindly treated, &amp; learn tricks easily – (such
               as Milner's) – but the whole thing is liable to awful abuses &amp; cruelties.</p>

            <pb n="4" facs="uoedh_hl_h.3175_4.jpg"/>


            <p> There are a few things that have happened lately which cheer one. The passing of the
               plumage Bill in <placeName ref="#pl:America">america</placeName>, &amp; the rending
               of the feathers from the hats of callous women delights me. But I fear the inspection
               of the poor pit ponies is very unsatisfactory – &amp; our <persName
                  ref="#ps:ReginaldMcKenna">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> McKenna</persName> has
               behaved badly about it.</p>

            <p> I hope you are getting fond of the live "<placeName ref="#pl:Wessex"
                  >Wessex</placeName>"? –</p>

            <p> This place, as I think I told you, is quite astonishingly rural. In some of the
               country roads &amp; lanes one might be a hundred miles from <placeName
                  ref="#pl:London">London</placeName>, instead of 23.</p>

            <p> I hear from an old friend, <persName ref="#ps:FrancisChanning">Lord
                  Channing</persName>, a very busy</p>

            <pb n="5" facs="uoedh_hl_h.3175_5.jpg"/>
            <ab>
               <seg xml:id="h3175a" corresp="m01" style="text-orientation: sideways-left">politician
                  in old days, that he is now, very sensibly, reading your books. I know he
                  will</seg>
            </ab>

            <ab>
               <seg xml:id="h3175b" corresp="m02" style="text-orientation: sideways-left">
                  appreciate much of them very keenly. You ask about the soil – here. It is chalky,
                  &amp; the air, I think very bracing – </seg>
            </ab>
            <pb n="6" facs="uoedh_hl_h.3175_6.jpg"/>
            <ab>
               <seg xml:id="h3175c" corresp="m03" style="text-orientation: sideways-left"> I hope to
                  do a great deal in encouraging birds in the orchard. Please give many messages to
                     <persName ref="#ps:FlorenceHardy">Miss Dugdale</persName> &amp; my love.
                  Someday you &amp; she must come &amp; see me here. – By the way, I went to a
                  little party at <persName ref="#ps:EdmundGosse">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>
                     Gosse</persName>'s – the first I had been to. They were so kind in getting of
                  interesting people to come &amp; talk to me. I </seg>
            </ab>
            <pb n="7" facs="uoedh_hl_h.3175_7.jpg"/>
            <ab>
               <seg xml:id="h3175d" corresp="m04" style="text-orientation: sideways-left">met
                     <persName ref="#ps:BranderMatthews">D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>
                     Brander</persName>, &amp; also went to hear his lecture on "<name type="play"
                     >Hamlet</name>". Many good wishes for 1914.</seg>
            </ab>

            <closer xml:id="h3175e" corresp="m05" style="text-orientation: sideways-left">
               <salute><choice><abbr>Y<hi rend="superscript"
                     >r</hi></abbr><expan>Your</expan></choice>
                  <choice><abbr>affec</abbr><expan>affectionate</expan></choice> friend.</salute>
               <signed>F.H.</signed>
            </closer>

